<TITLE> Condoleeza Rice pledges assistance in Sidr aftermath </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 19 (bdnews24.com) US Secretary of State Condoleeza Rice has pledged support and assistance in the aftermath of Cyclone Sidr, in a message from Washington Monday. "We extend our deepest sympathies to the people of Bangladesh following this major natural disaster, and we stand ready to assist further," Rice said in a statement sent to the US Embassy in Dhaka. The United States is calling into action a multitude of US government disaster relief agencies and departments, the statement said. "While the US and other donors will continue with aid efforts in the aftermath of Sidr, the effects of the cyclone were mitigated and many lives saved thanks to the investments in disaster preparedness made by the Government of Bangladesh, working with USAID," Rice said. The US Agency for International Development (USAID) provided $100,000 immediately after the cyclone and has deployed a five-person disaster assessment team to Bangladesh to work alongside local authorities in assisting with the relief and recovery efforts, the statement said. USAID is now sending an additional $2 million in emergency funds for water and sanitation programs and to provide shelter materials to those in need. A portion of this funding will also be provided to humanitarian organisations currently working in the affected areas, according to the Secretary of State. At the request of the US Embassy in Bangladesh, US Pacific Command has sent a 23-man Humanitarian Assistance Survey Team of Marines to the southern coast of Bangladesh. In addition, two US Navy ships, expected to arrive in 5 to 7 days, have been ordered to move in the direction of Bangladesh in the event that the Government of Bangladesh requests assistance, Rice said. The ships each carry 20 or more helicopters that can be used for medical evacuations and surveying affected a
